document.title: Texas Essential Knowledge and Skills for Mathematics

BF567D70DFE7013117F268A86D17958E.description: display, explain, and justify mathematical ideas and arguments using precise mathematical language in written or oral communication.

BF5616A0DFE7013117F168A86D17958E.description: analyze mathematical relationships to connect and communicate mathematical ideas; and

BF55C090DFE7013117F068A86D17958E.description: create and use representations to organize, record, and communicate mathematical ideas;

BF556790DFE7013117EF68A86D17958E.description: communicate mathematical ideas, reasoning, and their implications using multiple representations, including symbols, diagrams, graphs, and language as appropriate;

BF550340DFE7013117EE68A86D17958E.description: select tools, including real objects, manipulatives, paper and pencil, and technology as appropriate, and techniques, including mental math, estimation, and number sense as appropriate, to solve problems;

BF549740DFE7013117ED68A86D17958E.description: use a problem-solving model that incorporates analyzing given information, formulating a plan or strategy, determining a solution, justifying the solution, and evaluating the problem-solving process and the reasonableness of the solution;

BF542170DFE7013117EC68A86D17958E.description: apply mathematics to problems arising in everyday life, society, and the workplace;

BF53CA30DFE7013117EB68A86D17958E.description: Knowledge and skills: mathematical process standards. The student uses mathematical processes to acquire and demonstrate mathematical understanding. The student is expected to:

BF5321F0DFE7013117E968A86D17958E.description: communicate statistical results in oral and written formats using appropriate statistical and nontechnical language.

BF52C710DFE7013117E868A86D17958E.description: justify the design and the conclusion(s) of statistical studies, including the methods used; and

BF525F70DFE7013117E768A86D17958E.description: report results of statistical studies to a particular audience, including selecting an appropriate presentation format, creating graphical data displays, and interpreting results in terms of the question studied;

BF520A00DFE7013117E668A86D17958E.description: analyze possible sources of data variability, including those that can be controlled and those that cannot be controlled;

BF51AE50DFE7013117E568A86D17958E.description: create data displays for given data sets to investigate, compare, and estimate center, shape, spread, and unusual features of the data;

BF514C10DFE7013117E468A86D17958E.description: determine possible sources of statistical bias in a study and how bias may affect the validity of the results;

BF50F390DFE7013117E368A86D17958E.description: identify the variables to be used in a study;

BF5097A0DFE7013117E268A86D17958E.description: identify the population of interest for a statistical investigation, select an appropriate sampling technique, and collect data;

BF5041B0DFE7013117E168A86D17958E.description: determine the need for and purpose of a statistical investigation and what type of statistical analysis can be used to answer a specific question or set of questions;

BF4FE730DFE7013117E068A86D17958E.description: describe strengths and weaknesses of sampling techniques, data and graphical displays, and interpretations of summary statistics and other results appearing in a study, including reports published in the media;

BF4F8420DFE7013117DF68A86D17958E.description: identify potential misuses of statistics to justify particular conclusions, including assertions of a cause-and-effect relationship rather than an association, and missteps or fallacies in logical reasoning;

BF4F2280DFE7013117DE68A86D17958E.description: interpret and compare statistical results using appropriate technology given a margin of error;

BF4EC190DFE7013117DD68A86D17958E.description: identify limitations and lack of relevant information in studies reporting statistical information, especially when studies are reported in condensed form;

BF4E69C0DFE7013117DC68A86D17958E.description: determine the validity of logical arguments that include compound conditional statements by constructing truth tables;

BF4E1050DFE7013117DB68A86D17958E.description: calculate expected value to analyze mathematical fairness, payoff, and risk;

BF4DB4A0DFE7013117DA68A86D17958E.description: use probabilities to make and justify decisions about risks in everyday life;

BF4D4760DFE7013117D968A86D17958E.description: interpret conditional probabilities and probabilities of compound events by analyzing representations to make decisions in problem situations;

BF4CD870DFE7013117D868A86D17958E.description: calculate conditional probabilities and probabilities of compound events using tree diagrams, Venn diagrams, area models, and formulas;

BF4C73B0DFE7013117D768A86D17958E.description: use the Addition Rule, P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B) - P(A and B), in mathematical and real-world problems;

BF4C12C0DFE7013117D668A86D17958E.description: use a two-way frequency table as a sample space to identify whether two events are independent and to interpret the results;

BF4B92D0DFE7013117D568A86D17958E.description: Probabilistic and statistical reasoning. The student uses the process standards in mathematics to generate new understandings of probability and statistics. The student analyzes statistical information and evaluates risk and return to connect mathematical ideas and make informed decisions. The student applies a problem-solving model and statistical methods to design and conduct a study that addresses one or more particular question(s). The student uses multiple representations to communicate effectively the results of student-generated statistical studies and the critical analysis of published statistical studies. The student is expected to:

BF4B1F30DFE7013117D468A86D17958E.description: create, represent, and analyze mathematical models and appropriate representations, including formulas and amortization tables, for various types of loans and investments to determine the best option for a given situation.

BF4ACB90DFE7013117D368A86D17958E.description: create, represent, and analyze mathematical models for expenditures, including those involving credit, to determine the best option for a given situation; and

BF4A7570DFE7013117D268A86D17958E.description: create, represent, and analyze mathematical models for various types of income calculations to determine the best option for a given situation;

BF4A1E80DFE7013117D168A86D17958E.description: determine or analyze an appropriate piecewise model for problem situations;

BF49C270DFE7013117D068A86D17958E.description: determine or analyze an appropriate cyclical model for problem situations that can be modeled with periodic functions;

BF496030DFE7013117CF68A86D17958E.description: determine or analyze an appropriate growth or decay model for problem situations, including linear, exponential, and logistic functions;

BF490A60DFE7013117CE68A86D17958E.description: describe the degree to which uncorrelated variables may or may not be related and analyze situations where correlated variables do or do not indicate a cause-and-effect relationship;

BF48B380DFE7013117CD68A86D17958E.description: collect numerical bivariate data to create a scatterplot, select a function to model the data, justify the model selection, and use the model to interpret results and make predictions;

BF484D60DFE7013117CC68A86D17958E.description: Algebraic reasoning (expressions, equations, and generalized relationships). The student applies the process standards in mathematics to create and analyze mathematical models of everyday situations to make informed decisions related to earning, investing, spending, and borrowing money by appropriate, proficient, and efficient use of tools, including technology. The student uses mathematical relationships to make connections and predictions. The student judges the validity of a prediction and uses mathematical models to represent, analyze, and solve dynamic real-world problems. The student is expected to:

BF47D940DFE7013117CB68A86D17958E.description: select and apply an algorithm of interest to solve real-life problems such as problems using recursion or iteration involving population growth or decline, fractals, and compound interest; the validity in recorded and transmitted data using checksums and hashing; sports rankings, weighted class rankings, and search engine rankings; and problems involving scheduling or routing situations using vertex-edge graphs, critical paths, Euler paths, and minimal spanning trees and communicate to peers the application of the algorithm in precise mathematical and nontechnical language.

BF475CB0DFE7013117CA68A86D17958E.description: analyze various voting and selection processes to compare results in given situations; and

BF470280DFE7013117C968A86D17958E.description: use arrays to efficiently manage large collections of data and add, subtract, and multiply matrices to solve applied problems, including geometric transformations;

BF46A2D0DFE7013117C868A86D17958E.description: solve problems involving large quantities using combinatorics;

BF462D70DFE7013117C768A86D17958E.description: solve geometric problems involving indirect measurement, including similar triangles, the Pythagorean Theorem, Law of Sines, Law of Cosines, and the use of dynamic geometry software;

BF45C230DFE7013117C668A86D17958E.description: solve problems involving quantities that are not easily measured using proportionality;

BF456900DFE7013117C568A86D17958E.description: apply and analyze published ratings, weighted averages, and indices to make informed decisions;

BF450F50DFE7013117C468A86D17958E.description: use precision and accuracy in real-life situations related to measurement and significant figures;

BF44B370DFE7013117C368A86D17958E.description: Numeric reasoning. The student applies the process standards in mathematics to generate new understandings by extending existing knowledge. The student generates new mathematical understandings through problems involving numerical data that arise in everyday life, society, and the workplace. The student extends existing knowledge and skills to analyze real-world situations. The student is expected to:

BF445650DFE7013117C268A86D17958E.description: display, explain, and justify mathematical ideas and arguments using precise mathematical language in written or oral communication.

BF43EFE0DFE7013117C168A86D17958E.description: analyze mathematical relationships to connect and communicate mathematical ideas; and

BF4330E0DFE7013117BF68A86D17958E.description: communicate mathematical ideas, reasoning, and their implications using multiple representations, including symbols, diagrams, graphs, and language as appropriate;

BF42CC40DFE7013117BE68A86D17958E.description: select tools, including real objects, manipulatives, paper and pencil, and technology as appropriate, and techniques, including mental math, estimation, and number sense as appropriate, to solve problems;

BF425D10DFE7013117BD68A86D17958E.description: use a problem-solving model that incorporates analyzing given information, formulating a plan or strategy, determining a solution, justifying the solution, and evaluating the problem-solving process and the reasonableness of the solution;

BF41FFB0DFE7013117BC68A86D17958E.description: apply mathematics to problems arising in everyday life, society, and the workplace;

BF41A9C0DFE7013117BB68A86D17958E.description: Mathematical process standards. The student uses mathematical processes to acquire and demonstrate mathematical understanding. The student is expected to:

BF32F160DFE70131179368A86D17958E.description: communicate methods used, analyses conducted, and conclusions drawn for a data-analysis project through the use of one or more of the following: a written report, a visual display, an oral report, or a multi-media presentation.

BF329870DFE70131179268A86D17958E.description: formulate a meaningful question, determine the data needed to answer the question, gather the appropriate data, analyze the data, and draw reasonable conclusions; and

BF323DF0DFE70131179168A86D17958E.description: Mathematical modeling in social sciences. The student applies mathematical processes to design a study and use graphical, numerical, and analytical techniques to communicate the results of the study. The student is expected to:

BF40F340DFE7013117B968A86D17958E.description: use regression methods available through technology to model linear and exponential functions, interpret correlations, and make predictions.

BF407660DFE7013117B868A86D17958E.description: analyze marketing claims based on graphs and statistics from electronic and print media and justify the validity of stated or implied conclusions; and

BF4002B0DFE7013117B768A86D17958E.description: use data from a sample to estimate population mean or population proportion;

BF3FAB30DFE7013117B668A86D17958E.description: distinguish the purposes and differences among types of research, including surveys, experiments, and observational studies;

BF3F5360DFE7013117B568A86D17958E.description: analyze numerical data using measures of central tendency (mean, median, and mode) and variability (range, interquartile range or IQR, and standard deviation) in order to make inferences with normal distributions;

BF3EFF80DFE7013117B468A86D17958E.description: interpret information from various graphs, including line graphs, bar graphs, circle graphs, histograms, scatterplots, dot plots, stem-and-leaf plots, and box and whisker plots, to draw conclusions from the data and determine the strengths and weaknesses of conclusions;

BF3EA730DFE7013117B368A86D17958E.description: Mathematical modeling in social sciences. The student applies mathematical processes and mathematical models to analyze data as it applies to social sciences. The student is expected to:

BF3E4D30DFE7013117B268A86D17958E.description: use experiments to determine the reasonableness of a theoretical model such as binomial or geometric.

BF3DF9E0DFE7013117B168A86D17958E.description: compare theoretical to empirical probability; and

BF3DA340DFE7013117B068A86D17958E.description: determine the number of ways an event may occur using combinations, permutations, and the Fundamental Counting Principle;

BF3D47D0DFE7013117AF68A86D17958E.description: Mathematical modeling in social sciences. The student applies mathematical processes to determine the number of elements in a finite sample space and compute the probability of an event. The student is expected to:

BF3CED70DFE7013117AE68A86D17958E.description: use scale factors with two-dimensional and three-dimensional objects to demonstrate proportional and non-proportional changes in surface area and volume as applied to fields.

BF3C8EF0DFE7013117AD68A86D17958E.description: use geometric transformations, proportions, and periodic motion to describe mathematical patterns and structure in music; and

BF3C3BA0DFE7013117AC68A86D17958E.description: use similarity, geometric transformations, symmetry, and perspective drawings to describe mathematical patterns and structure in art and photography;

BF3BE830DFE7013117AB68A86D17958E.description: use trigonometric ratios and functions available through technology to model periodic behavior in art and music;

BF3B8710DFE7013117AA68A86D17958E.description: Mathematical modeling in fine arts. The student uses mathematical processes with algebra and geometry to study patterns and analyze data as it applies to fine arts. The student is expected to:

BF3B1B50DFE7013117A968A86D17958E.description: use trigonometric ratios to calculate distances and angle measures as applied to fields.

BF3A9740DFE7013117A868A86D17958E.description: use the Pythagorean Theorem and special right-triangle relationships to calculate distances; and

BF3A35E0DFE7013117A768A86D17958E.description: use scale factors with two-dimensional and three-dimensional objects to demonstrate proportional and non-proportional changes in surface area and volume as applied to fields;

BF39D8E0DFE7013117A668A86D17958E.description: use similarity, geometric transformations, symmetry, and perspective drawings to describe mathematical patterns and structure in architecture;

BF397F70DFE7013117A568A86D17958E.description: Mathematical modeling in science and engineering. The student applies mathematical processes with algebra and geometry to study patterns and analyze data as it applies to architecture and engineering. The student is expected to:

BF391D80DFE7013117A468A86D17958E.description: use quadratic functions to model motion.

BF38B5D0DFE7013117A368A86D17958E.description: use exponential models available through technology to model growth and decay in areas, including radioactive decay; and

BF386000DFE7013117A268A86D17958E.description: use proportionality and inverse variation to describe physical laws such as Hook's Law, Newton's Second Law of Motion, and Boyle's Law;

BF380D00DFE7013117A168A86D17958E.description: Mathematical modeling in science and engineering. The student applies mathematical processes with algebraic techniques to study patterns and analyze data as it applies to science. The student is expected to:

BF37BA10DFE7013117A068A86D17958E.description: analyze types of savings options involving simple and compound interest and compare relative advantages of these options.

BF3763E0DFE70131179F68A86D17958E.description: investigate and compare investment options, including stocks, bonds, annuities, certificates of deposit, and retirement plans; and

BF370540DFE70131179E68A86D17958E.description: analyze and compare coverage options and rates in insurance;

BF36A930DFE70131179D68A86D17958E.description: Mathematical modeling in personal finance. The student uses mathematical processes with algebraic formulas, numerical techniques, and graphs to solve problems related to financial planning. The student is expected to:

BF364240DFE70131179C68A86D17958E.description: use technology to create amortization models to investigate automobile financing and compare buying a vehicle to leasing a vehicle.

BF35D810DFE70131179B68A86D17958E.description: use technology to create amortization models to investigate home financing and compare buying a home to renting a home; and

BF3577C0DFE70131179A68A86D17958E.description: analyze personal credit options in retail purchasing and compare relative advantages and disadvantages of each option;

BF3516A0DFE70131179968A86D17958E.description: use formulas to generate tables to display series of payments for loan amortizations resulting from financed purchases;

BF34B930DFE70131179868A86D17958E.description: Mathematical modeling in personal finance. The student uses mathematical processes with algebraic formulas, graphs, and amortization modeling to solve problems involving credit. The student is expected to:

BF345900DFE70131179768A86D17958E.description: analyze data to make decisions about banking, including options for online banking, checking accounts, overdraft protection, processing fees, and debit card/ATM fees.

BF3401E0DFE70131179668A86D17958E.description: solve problems involving personal taxes; and

BF33AA60DFE70131179568A86D17958E.description: use rates and linear functions to solve problems involving personal finance and budgeting, including compensations and deductions;

BF3348F0DFE70131179468A86D17958E.description: Mathematical modeling in personal finance. The student uses mathematical processes with graphical and numerical techniques to study patterns and analyze data related to personal finance. The student is expected to:

BF31DF60DFE70131179068A86D17958E.description: display, explain, and justify mathematical ideas and arguments using precise mathematical language in written or oral communication.

BF3176D0DFE70131178F68A86D17958E.description: analyze mathematical relationships to connect and communicate mathematical ideas; and

BF2F1C90DFE70131178968A86D17958E.description: Mathematical process standards. The student uses mathematical processes to acquire and demonstrate mathematical understanding. The student is expected to:

BF2E68B0DFE70131178768A86D17958E.description: generate and solve trigonometric equations in mathematical and real-world problems.

BF2E0EA0DFE70131178668A86D17958E.description: use trigonometric identities such as reciprocal, quotient, Pythagorean, cofunctions, even/odd, and sum and difference identities for cosine and sine to simplify trigonometric expressions; and

BF2DBBC0DFE70131178568A86D17958E.description: solve rational inequalities with real coefficients by applying a variety of techniques and write the solution set of the rational inequality in interval notation in mathematical and real-world problems;

BF2D6810DFE70131178468A86D17958E.description: solve polynomial inequalities with real coefficients by applying a variety of techniques and write the solution set of the polynomial inequality in interval notation in mathematical and real-world problems;

BF2D1440DFE70131178368A86D17958E.description: solve polynomial equations with real coefficients by applying a variety of techniques in mathematical and real-world problems;

BF2CBD90DFE70131178268A86D17958E.description: generate and solve exponential equations in mathematical and real-world problems;

BF2C5870DFE70131178168A86D17958E.description: generate and solve logarithmic equations in mathematical and real-world problems;

BF2BF860DFE70131178068A86D17958E.description: use the properties of logarithms to evaluate or transform logarithmic expressions;

BF2B95E0DFE70131177F68A86D17958E.description: apply the Binomial Theorem for the expansion of (a + b)<sup>n</sup> in powers of a and b for a positive integer n, where a and b are any numbers;

BF2B34F0DFE70131177E68A86D17958E.description: calculate the n<sup>th</sup> term of a geometric series, the n<sup>th</sup> partial sum of a geometric series, and sum of an infinite geometric series when it exists;

BF2ADB80DFE70131177D68A86D17958E.description: represent arithmetic series and geometric series using sigma notation;

BF2A75D0DFE70131177C68A86D17958E.description: calculate the n<sup>th</sup> term and the n<sup>th</sup> partial sum of an arithmetic series in mathematical and real-world problems;

BF2A1DF0DFE70131177B68A86D17958E.description: represent arithmetic sequences and geometric sequences using recursive formulas;

BF29BF10DFE70131177A68A86D17958E.description: evaluate finite sums and geometric series, when possible, written in sigma notation;

BF294DE0DFE70131177968A86D17958E.description: Algebraic reasoning. The student uses process standards in mathematics to evaluate expressions, describe patterns, formulate models, and solve equations and inequalities using properties, procedures, or algorithms. The student is expected to:

BF28ED60DFE70131177868A86D17958E.description: apply vector addition and multiplication of a vector by a scalar in mathematical and real-world problems.

BF289370DFE70131177768A86D17958E.description: represent the addition of vectors and the multiplication of a vector by a scalar geometrically and symbolically; and

BF284050DFE70131177668A86D17958E.description: use vectors to model situations involving magnitude and direction;

BF27EBD0DFE70131177568A86D17958E.description: use the Law of Cosines in mathematical and real-world problems;

BF279290DFE70131177468A86D17958E.description: use the Law of Sines in mathematical and real-world problems;

BF272D10DFE70131177368A86D17958E.description: use trigonometry in mathematical and real-world problems, including directional bearing;

BF26C680DFE70131177268A86D17958E.description: determine the value of trigonometric ratios of angles and solve problems involving trigonometric ratios in mathematical and real-world problems;

BF266630DFE70131177168A86D17958E.description: represent angles in radians or degrees based on the concept of rotation in mathematical and real-world problems, including linear and angular velocity;

BF260ED0DFE70131177068A86D17958E.description: represent angles in radians or degrees based on the concept of rotation and find the measure of reference angles and angles in standard position;

BF25B940DFE70131176F68A86D17958E.description: describe the relationship between degree and radian measure on the unit circle;

BF255E60DFE70131176E68A86D17958E.description: determine the relationship between the unit circle and the definition of a periodic function to evaluate trigonometric functions in mathematical and real-world problems;

BF24FB00DFE70131176D68A86D17958E.description: Number and measure. The student uses process standards in mathematics to apply appropriate techniques, tools, and formulas to calculate measures in mathematical and real-world problems. The student is expected to:

BF24A440DFE70131176C68A86D17958E.description: use the characteristics of a hyperbola to write the equation of a hyperbola with center (h, k).

BF244C00DFE70131176B68A86D17958E.description: use the characteristics of an ellipse to write the equation of an ellipse with center (h, k); and

BF239270DFE70131176968A86D17958E.description: determine the conic section formed when a plane intersects a double-napped cone;

BF22CF50DFE70131176768A86D17958E.description: graph points in the polar coordinate system and convert between rectangular coordinates and polar coordinates;

BF21B6C0DFE70131176468A86D17958E.description: graph a set of parametric equations;

BF1F9800DFE70131175E68A86D17958E.description: determine various types of discontinuities in the interval (-∞, ∞) as they relate to functions and explore the limitations of the graphing calculator as it relates to the behavior of the function around discontinuities;

BF1ECAA0DFE70131175C68A86D17958E.description: analyze and describe end behavior of functions, including exponential, logarithmic, rational, polynomial, and power functions, using infinity notation to communicate this characteristic in mathematical and real-world problems;

BF1E5F80DFE70131175B68A86D17958E.description: determine and analyze the key features of exponential, logarithmic, rational, polynomial, power, trigonometric, inverse trigonometric, and piecewise defined functions, including step functions such as domain, range, symmetry, relative maximum, relative minimum, zeros, asymptotes, and intervals over which the function is increasing or decreasing;

BF1DE5C0DFE70131175A68A86D17958E.description: graph arcsin x and arccos x and describe the limitations on the domain;

BF1D9310DFE70131175968A86D17958E.description: graph functions, including exponential, logarithmic, sine, cosine, rational, polynomial, and power functions and their transformations, including af(x), f(x) + d, f(x - c), f(bx) for specific values of a, b, c, and d, in mathematical and real-world problems;

BF1D3E80DFE70131175868A86D17958E.description: graph exponential, logarithmic, rational, polynomial, power, trigonometric, inverse trigonometric, and piecewise defined functions, including step functions;

BF1CE930DFE70131175768A86D17958E.description: determine an inverse function, when it exists, for a given function over its domain or a subset of its domain and represent the inverse using multiple representations;

BF1C8DC0DFE70131175668A86D17958E.description: describe symmetry of graphs of even and odd functions;

BF1B7EA0DFE70131175368A86D17958E.description: use the composition of two functions to model and solve real-world problems;
